{
  "texts": [
    "As exemplified in Bayesian statistics, independence is an important property when computing a joint conditional probability distribution.",
    "The linear output layer converts each of the final contextualized tokens in the output matrix Z to probability distributions Y over the fixed vocabulary.",
    "The output matrix for a single training batch has the dimensions (sequence length × vocabulary size) = (n × m).",
    "Each vector in the output sequence contains a set of m logit values representing the probability distribution of that token over the entire vocabulary.",
    "The logit value in each position of the vector corresponds to the probability that the predicted token is the one at that position in the vocabulary."
  ]
}